## Answer

The pi SDK provides **three official mechanisms** to restrict tools for subagents, none of which require regex-based bash command filtering:

### 1. `createAgentSession()` `tools` allowlist (best for subagent creation)

```typescript
import { createAgentSession } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

// Subagent with NO bash, read-only + grep
const { session } = await createAgentSession({
  tools: ["read", "grep", "find", "ls"],  // bash not listed = never registered
  // also available:
  // excludeTools: ["bash"],  // denylist after allowlist
  // noTools: "all",          // disable ALL tools
  // noTools: "builtin",      // disable built-ins, keep extensions
});
```

The `tools` array is an **allowlist**. Only listed tool names get built-in tool definitions created. Tool `bash` is never instantiated, never appears in system prompt, never reaches LLM. No regex. No interception.

### 2. `pi.setActiveTools()` in extensions (runtime dynamic)

```typescript
pi.on("session_start", async (_event, ctx) => {
  // Remove bash from active tools at runtime
  const active = pi.getActiveTools();
  pi.setActiveTools(active.filter(name => name !== "bash"));
});
```

Source: `docs/extensions.md` — `pi.getActiveTools()`, `pi.getAllTools()`, `pi.setActiveTools(names)`.

### 3. `tool_call` extension event (intercept at framework level)

```typescript
pi.on("tool_call", async (event, ctx) => {
  if (event.toolName === "bash") {
    return { block: true, reason: "Bash not allowed for this agent" };
  }
});
```

Returns `{ block: true }` — tool never executes. The `tool_call` event fires **after** the LLM decides to call a tool but **before** execution. This is the framework-level interception point.

Source: `docs/extensions.md` Tool Events section, `dist/core/extensions/runner.js` line 639 (`emitToolCall`), `dist/core/agent-session.js` line 181 (`_installAgentToolHooks`).

